# Auth & RBAC

Better Auth is configured in `packages/auth/src/auth.ts` (exported as `auth` from `@repo/auth/auth`) with the `organization` plugin and `dynamicAccessControl` enabled. The browser client is `packages/auth/src/auth-client.ts` (`@repo/auth/auth-client`). Sessions persist in PostgreSQL via Drizzle — tables live in `packages/db/src/schema.ts` (`user`, `session`, `account`, `organization`, `member`, `invitation`, `organizationRole`).

## Access control model
`packages/auth/src/permissions.ts` defines the `statement` (resources → actions) and built-in roles:
- Resources/actions: `organization` (update, delete), `member` (invite, update, remove), `invitation` (create, cancel), `ac` (create, read, update, delete), `project` (create, read, update, delete).
- Roles: `owner` (all), `admin` (all except `organization.delete`), `member` (`project.read`).
- `ac` is the resource that gates managing custom roles themselves — name it `ac` exactly; it is what the roles UI checks.

Custom roles are created at runtime via the `role` router (`auth.api.createOrgRole`) and stored in `organizationRoleTable`.

## Server-side enforcement
In `packages/api/src/middleware/rbac.ts`:
- `orgProcedure` requires `session.activeOrganizationId`, exposing it as `ctx.orgId`.
- `permissionProcedure(resource, action)` builds on `orgProcedure` and calls `auth.api.hasPermission`.
- `assertInScope(row, ctx)` throws `NOT_FOUND` unless `row.organizationId === ctx.orgId`.

Routers use these — e.g. `permissionProcedure('project', 'create')` in `packages/api/src/router/project.ts`.

## UI gating
`<Can>` (`apps/web/src/components/can.tsx`) wraps the `usePermission` hook (`apps/web/src/hooks/use-permission.ts`), which calls `authClient.organization.hasPermission`. Sidebar links carry a `permission` field in `apps/web/src/lib/constants.ts`.

```tsx
{{{{raw}}}}
<Can permissions={{ project: ['create'] }}>
  <CreateProjectButton />
</Can>
{{{{/raw}}}}
```
